# No em dashes in content

When writing or editing **LLM-produced text** in `docs/**/*.mdx`, do not use em dashes (`—`) or en dashes as punctuation (`–`).

## Do not edit

- `slug:` (and any URL/path identifiers)
- `tags:`, `authors:`, `image:`, `draft:`, `sidebar_*`, imports, file paths
- Fenced code blocks (``` ... ```)
- Third-party quotes (keep original punctuation)

## Do edit (LLM prose)

- Body copy: paragraphs, lists, tables, admonitions
- `title:` and `description:` in frontmatter (quote YAML values if they contain `:`)
- Markdown headings (`#`, `##`, …)
- `<Details summary="...">` text

## Use instead

| Instead of em dash | Prefer |
| --- | --- |
| Parenthetical aside | Commas, parentheses, or a new sentence |
| Title separator | Colon (`:`) or pipe (`\|`) |
| Range or contrast | Colon, period, or rephrase |
| List lead-in | Colon |
| Numeric/circled ranges (`2–3`, `①–③`) | Hyphen (`2-3`, `①-③`) |

## Examples

```markdown
# BAD
An intent router maps requests to routes — not to answers.
LangChain vs LangGraph — When to Use What

# GOOD
An intent router maps requests to routes, not to answers.
LangChain vs LangGraph: When to Use What
```

## Before finishing

1. Skip every `slug:` line unchanged.
2. Scan only LLM prose in changed `.mdx` files for `—` and `–`.
3. Quote `title:` / `description:` values when the result contains `:`.
4. Run `node scripts/fix-em-dashes-docs.mjs` for bulk cleanup (docs only).
